quote.p:
The first person in Baghdad to become aware of this method and to alert others to it and treat patients accordingly and dispense with other methods was shaykh Abū Manṣūr Ṣāʿid ibn Bishr ibn ʿAbdūs the physician, may God show him mercy. He would treat patients by letting their blood, and giving them cooling and moisture-inducing remedies and would not allow patients to take food. This regimen was very successful and he became foremost of his time after having been a bloodletter in the hospital. He became the chief physician upon whom kings depended for their regimens. In the hospital, Ṣāʿid ibn Bishr ibn ʿAbdūs changed the regimen of the patients from the hot salves (
maʿājīn
) and pungent medicaments that were in use to barley water and the juice of seeds, and this method of treatment worked wonders.

