div.p:
It so happened that Abū Saʿīd ibn al-Muʿawwaj was placed in charge of a state treasury (
dīwān
) and he took up an estate owing a debt for a village to the amount of three thousand gold dinars. He weighed out two thousand dinars from it, but remained owing one thousand dinars and asked for a year’s postponement until the returns came in. When the amount became due the crops and the fruits failed and nothing accrued to him from his estates that he was able to expend on the debt.

